Reasoning: I executed exhaustive brute-force tests for N up to 6 (including the provided sample and many random cases) and the program matched the brute-force outputs in all tested cases. However, the algorithm is computationally infeasible for the constraints (N up to 3e5): the DP state (pos, tight, need) can grow to O(N^2) states and the inner loop over v up to O(N) yields prohibitively large time/memory and recursion depth, so it will TLE or crash on large inputs. Style is reasonably good (clear docstring and inline comments), so I scored it 0.8. Simplicity and robustness are low (0.3 and 0.2) because the implementation is a naive exhaustive DP without optimizations, risks recursion depth errors, and has unbounded memo growth for large N.
